[1] Guinea outbreak
- Wed 17 Feb 2021. Index case
[Guinee Matin (in French, machine trans., edited)]
https://guineematin.com/2021/02/17/6-deces-dus-a-ebola-en-guinee-une-grave-erreur-qui-coute-cher/
[Byline: Foromo Gbouo Lamah]

A serious error by the agents of the Goueke health center would have favored the spread of the Ebola virus, which reappeared recently in this sub-prefecture located more than 40 km [25 mi] from the city of Nzerekore (in southern Guinea). The latter would have made a false diagnosis on a patient they received in December 2020 and who would be the 1st case of Ebola.

It was the health authorities of Nzerekore who announced the news on Wed 17 Feb 2021, reports the correspondent of <Guineematin.com> on the spot. Contrary to what has been announced so far, the Ebola virus did not reappear at the end of January 2021 in Guinea, but long before. The nurse who died [in January 2021] is therefore not the 1st victim of this disease.

Her stepmother [or possibly her mother-in-law based on conflicting translations. - Mod.JH], a 70-year-old who died in December 2020 at the Goueke health center, is said to be patient zero (the 1st case). In any case, this is what the daily report of the Ebola hemorrhagic fever response teams published this Wed 17 Feb 2021 in Nzerekore.

According to this report, the old woman was hospitalized at the Goueke health center after developing a vaginal hemorrhage. Health workers who diagnosed her concluded that she had "severe anemia." But, a few weeks after her death, the nurse who was caring for her and who happened to be her stepdaughter, fell ill and also died. Several people who attended her funeral subsequently fell ill, and 3 of them died.

This is why a few days after the tests revealing the presence of the Ebola virus disease in Goueke, the health authorities decided to count the old woman among the victims of Ebola, which makes 6 deaths caused by the epidemic since its resurgence in Guinea. Deaths, most of which are believed to be due to the false diagnosis made by the health workers who received the 1st patient, and which led to new contaminations.

Health authorities announced contacts went from 164 to 216 in Nzerekore.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
