[The question still remains: How did the stepmother of the nurse acquire Ebola? - Mod.LK]

- Wed 17 Feb 2021. 52 new contacts
[Guinee News (in French, machine trans., abridged, edited)]
https://www.guineenews.org/ebola-a-N'Zerekore-52-nouveaux-contacts-dont-6-deces-officiel/
[Byline: Alpha Oumar Balde]

Ebola in Nzerekore: 52 new contacts including 6 deaths (official)
A crisis meeting on the assessment of the Ebola virus epidemic was held this Wed 17 Feb 2021 at the headquarters of the prefecture of Nzerekore.

Since the detection of the 1st cases of Ebola in the locality of Goueke, concern has grown among the population where the number of infections and deaths continue to grow. This, despite awareness-raising and preventive measures put in place by the government to break the chain of contagion as quickly as possible.

To date, specialized health structures have reported 52 new contact cases, including 6 deaths.

The local health services indicate this now brings the number of contacts to 216 people, 2 isolated cases including one at high risk.

Of note, 100 hand-washing kits were made available to the hospital through the synergy of all partners active in the fight against Ebola.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall

- Wed 17 Feb 2021. Resurgence of Ebola amid COVID-19
[The Africa Report, abridged, edited]
https://www.theafricareport.com/66515/guinea-ebolas-resurgence-in-the-midst-of-covid-19/amp
[Byline: Diawo Barry]

More than 4 years after the end of the Ebola epidemic, Guinea is facing a new resurgence of the virus, amidst the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic.

The Guinean health authorities announced the resurgence of Ebola less than a month after the death of the 1st official victim, who was a nurse from Goueke, at the end of January [2021].

When Ebola last appeared in Guinea in 2013, it took 3 times as long before "the victims who succumbed to a mysterious disease in Guinee Forestiere" -- as reported by the local press at the time -- were actually identified as victims of the haemorrhagic fever.

At the time, the samples had been sent to the Pasteur Institutes in Dakar and Lyon for analysis. This time, the tests took place on the spot.

The Agence Nationale de Securite Sanitaire (ANSS/National Agency for Health Security), headed by doctor Sakoba Keita, who was the national coordinator for the fight against Ebola from 2014-2016, quickly came together with support from health minister Remy Lamah, already at the helm during the 1st epidemic. A joint mission was then deployed to Nzerekore, the capital of the south-eastern region, from which the disease originated, as it did in December 2013.

Identifying the chain of contamination [See section above on this one for most up-to-date 1st. - Mod.LK]

[Even if the 1st recorded victim [the nurse from Goueke] developed symptoms after the hospitalisation of her mother-in-law, who died in January [2021], the latter "presented very few symptoms that are typical of Ebola" says doctor Adama Kaba, regional health director of Nzerekore, whom we contacted.

"None of the women in the village who performed the old woman's funeral cleansing developed the disease," he continues. "On the other hand, some of the people who attended the nurse's funeral fell ill. For the time being, and until there is evidence to the contrary, the nurse is patient zero."

This nurse was hospitalised in a facility in Nzerekore, then at the indigenat [traditional medicine hospital], where she died. Her body was then buried in Goueke. The challenge now is to identify and follow up on all the contact cases along this journey.

"We have listed all the contact cases, about 100, 80% of which reside in the sub-prefecture of Goueke. Their health is currently being monitored by agents. We have started raising awareness through local radio stations and have called on the ANSS and other partners who are arriving to support us in the response," explains doctor Kaba.

Gatherings banned, markets closed, and vaccines expected
A series of measures have been announced. In a statement read on the evening of 15 Feb 2021 on state media, President Alpha Conde banned any gatherings of more than 5 people in Nzerekore. In the sub-prefecture of Goueke, markets will also be closed for a month.

Among other provisions,
- the Red Cross will now provide dignified and safe burials for suspected or confirmed cases;
- checkpoints have been set up, as well as measures to check body temperatures; and
- isolated households will receive food to limit travel.

The authorities have also said that vaccines will be made available. While a trial vaccine has been introduced, thanks in part to research carried out in Guinea, the stockpile there that dates from the end of the 1st epidemic in 2016 has expired.

Georges Alfred Ki-Zerbo, the World Health Organisation (WHO) representative in Guinea, says that the residents of Conakry are eagerly awaiting new doses of the vaccine.

"We are in contact with the regional office in Brazzaville and the headquarters in Geneva to secure vaccines that will strengthen the response," he said, assuring that the WHO is also fully mobilised. "The 1st steps have been taken to activate the emergency management system, as part of the WHO programme set up following previous Ebola epidemics in West Africa," he continued.

"We have delivered logistical material in order to implement the government's directives concerning the management of the Ebola virus disease. This material is composed of PPE. This emergency transport was facilitated by the United Nations system in Guinea."

Several health problems
Even though the Guinean authorities' response to the COVID-19 pandemic proves that they have learned from the experience of the 1st Ebola epidemic, it is important to remain prudent, warns the WHO representative.

"Guinea is facing a very complex health situation. These new cases of Ebola come on top of the COVID-19 context; yellow fever, which is raging in Koundara, near the border with Senegal; and the outbreaks of polio that are being contained through vaccination campaigns," says Ki-Zerbo.

"There are many health problems, and the health system remains fragile. We need to learn all the lessons and, above all, not forget the lesson about community involvement in the 1st infected households: we need to make sure that communities' perceptions, their sensitivity, and their approaches to solutions are taken into account."

An inclusive approach is all the more important since, during the 1st Ebola epidemic, people were initially reluctant to observe certain social-distancing measures. Burial rituals, traditionally carried out by family members of the deceased, had often continued despite the dangers posed.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall

- Wed 17 Feb 2021. IFRC situation report
[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC) abridged, edited]
https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/MDRGN012do.pdf

Guinea: Ebola virus disease outbreak emergency plan of action (EPoA) DREF Operation no. MDRGN0
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A. Situation analysis
---------------------
Description of the disaster
On 14 Feb 2021, the Government of Guinea declared a new outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in Goueke sub-prefecture, which is part of Nzerekore prefecture in Guinee Forrestiere Region. Following an alert by the director of the regional hospital of Nzerekore of cases of vomiting, bloody diarrhoea, and total haematuria, bleeding at the injection sites of 5 patients from the same family hospitalized in the intensive care unit and followed by a transfer to Conakry (CHU Donka). The surveillance team from the regional health authorities (DRS) and prefectural health authorities (DPS) went to the hospital and the subprefecture of Goueke, respectively, for an investigation.

Based on known information, 7 people have been infected to date including 3 deaths, 3 patients hospitalized in Nzerekore, and one hospitalized in Conakry. Although the 1st case was confirmed in February [2021], it is unclear when the outbreak started, which means the virus might have spread beyond the current known cases, and there have been at least 2 unsecure burials of community deaths. The origins of the outbreak are unknown for the moment, and all known cases so far are within the same family (Goueke and Nzerekore) and in people aged over 25 years.

As of 16 Feb 2021, a joint mission of the Ministry of Health has already deployed to support the Goueke team for the field assessment. Several actions have been launched to prevent transmission and identify new infections: case isolation, investigations and data collecting for tracing potential new cases, mobilization of vaccines and diagnostic kits, opening of a treatment centre, and safe and dignified burials to prevent post-mortem transmission. A national level coordination mechanism has also been launched to mobilize partners, while neighbouring countries including Cote d'Ivoire, Liberia, and Sierra Leone are on high alert.

As investigations and contact tracing are ongoing to determine the scale of the outbreak and the geography of the risk, all humanitarian partners are expected to meet on 19 Feb 2021 to strategize on intervention. The probable impact areas are the prefectures of Nzerekore, Guekedou, Macenta, Lola, Yomou, and Beyla. The number of people at risk in these areas is estimated at 1 042 251 inhabitants. The expected effect is a considerable increase in cases and the spread of the disease due to the displacement of infected people.

To note, Nzerekore region is the 3rd-most-populated region in Guinea, covering 18% of the national territory. It is at the same time the furthest from Conakry (870 km [540 mi] away), the most landlocked, and the least urbanized. Sociocultural conflicts (ethnic, religious, or socioeconomic) have led to unprecedented violence in Guinea Forest region since 2010. The region's rugged terrain makes access difficult, which highlights the isolation of several villages in the region.

The response to the COVID-19 epidemic has set a positive dynamic in terms of epidemic control and increased hygiene measures amongst the population to curb the spread of the disease. However, this should not be considered sufficient to prevent a 2014 scenario with the EVD outbreak spreading in the region. In that remote area, isolation of population and behaviours guided by fear of stigma and social impacts of the last Ebola outbreak remain an issue, and community burials are both standard practice and a high risk for rapid transmission of the virus.

In this context, the next few weeks will be crucial and must be spent building robust protection and control actions to avoid the spread of the outbreak.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall

