- Tue 16 Feb 2021. Timeline
[AllAfrica, Reuters, WHO report, abridged, edited]
https://allafrica.com/stories/202102170058.html

The Ebola virus has been detected in West Africa for the 1st time since the outbreak in 2013-2016. Here's a timeline of the key developments:

Guinea and the Democratic Republic of Congo are racing to contain fresh outbreaks of Ebola that have killed at least 4 people, amid fears the virus could spread across the region.

[Timeline of the main developments
----------------------------------
- 1 Jun 2020: Congo announces its 11th outbreak of Ebola since 1976, with a cluster of cases detected in its northwest Equateur province.
Congo is simultaneously battling the 10th outbreak in the northeastern North Kivu and Ituri provinces, which started in August 2018.
- 25 Jun 2020: Congo declares an end to the 10th outbreak in the northeast, which was the 2nd deadliest in the world, killing almost 2300 people.
- 18 Nov 2020: Congo announces the 11th outbreak of Ebola in Equateur province is over, after just under 6 months.
- 28 Jan 2021: A nurse who is thought to have been infected with Ebola dies in southeast Guinea's Nzerekore prefecture, near the border with Liberia and Ivory Coast, its 1st resurgence since the deadly 2013-2016 outbreak.
- 1 Feb 2021: The nurse's funeral takes place in Guinea, and 7 people who attend later report symptoms and test positive for Ebola.
- 7 Feb 2021: Congo announces a 12th outbreak of Ebola after a woman died in Butembo city in North Kivu Province.
- 14 Feb 2021: Guinea's health ministry declares a new outbreak of Ebola after 3 people die and 4 fall ill after attending the nurse's funeral on 1 Feb 2021.
The WHO announces it is working with health authorities in Liberia and Sierra Leone to beef up community surveillance of cases in border districts and strengthen testing capacity.
The WHO also reaches out to Ivory Coast, Mali, Senegal, and other countries at risk in the sub-region.
Congo reports a 4th new case of Ebola in Butembo.
- 15 Feb 2021: Guinea's Health Minister, Remy Lamah, says authorities are tracking down people who had contact with Ebola patients and will rush vaccines -- the 1st of which won regulatory approval in 2019 -- to the affected area.
[- Wed 17 Feb 2021: Guinee Matin reports [see section [1], above] that Nzerekore health authorities have said that, contrary to what has been announced so far, a 70-year-old who died at the Goueke health center in December 2020 is said to be patient zero (the 1st case). The nurse who died [in January 2021], the 70-year-old's stepdaughter, is therefore not the 1st victim of this disease. However, no reports, other than that single post, are listing the 70-year-old as the index case, possibly because she apparently never was diagnosed, although the chain of events points to her. - Mod.LK]

Unlike during the 2013-2016 outbreak, Lamah said Guinea has the capacity to halt the virus' resurgence due to improved treatments.

The WHO launches an Ebola vaccination campaign in Congo's Butembo city. Health workers at Matanda health centre, where the 1st Ebola patient was treated, are 1st to be vaccinated.

[Reporting: Nita Bhalla, editing: Katy Migiro]

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall

- Tue 16 Feb 2021. Ghana: response protocol initiated
[MyJoyOnline.com, abridged, edited]
https://www.myjoyonline.com/initiate-response-protocols-for-ebola-ghs-directs-all-hospitals/


The Ghana Health Service (GHS) has directed the management of all health facilities in the country to initiate response protocols for the Ebola virus disease (EVD).

To ensure that the nation is prepared to combat the virus, the GHS Director-General, Dr Patrick Aboagye, in a statement on Tuesday [16 Feb 2021] has asked all regional and district public health emergency management committees to include EVD in their agendas.

"Additionally, regions, districts, health facilities, ports, health units at all border posts, particularly, along the Western border, and all landing beaches are to heighten surveillance for EVD using the standard case definition," he stated.

The Director-General further advised Ghanaians to practice safety protocols, including regular hand washing, avoiding contact with animals, and desisting from eating bush meat.

"We are to take note and remind the general public that, under no circumstance, should public or private transport be used in transporting a suspected EVD case.

"They are to call for support from the Director of Health Services of respective districts, municipalities, or metropolis in the transfer of such persons to a health facility," he cautioned.

